         <abstract>
            <p>The Cahn-Hilliard equation is a nonlinear evolutionary equation that is of fourth order in space. In this paper a linearized finite difference scheme is derived by the method of reduction of order. It is proved that the scheme is uniquely solvable and convergent with the convergence rate of order two in a discrete L&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;-norm. The coefficient matrix of the difference system is symmetric and positive definite, so many well-known iterative methods (e.g. Gauss-Seidel, SOR) can be used to solve the system.</p>
          </abstract>
